2. MAP: Identify conflicts of interest, stakeholder roles, and audit governance
The MAP function of the NIST AI RMF establishes the context for the audit. It identifies the model's intended use, stakeholders, potential harm, and characterizes the dataset that the model will operate on. In this section, we also identify the stakeholders responsible for evaluating the system, since auditor independence and bias is itself a fairness concern.

2.1 System Description
Attribute	Value
System	Binary classifier predicting whether an individual's annual income exceeds $50,000
Dataset	UCI Adult (Census Income), 1994 U.S. Census Bureau data that contains roughly 45,000 records
Intended Use	Illustrative and educational
Sensitive Attributes	sex (Male / Female) and race (White / Non-White), as defined in the dataset
Potential Harm	Disparate denial of opportunity, reinforcement of historical wage and demographic inequities, denial of loans and other financial products
2.2 Stakeholder Map
The audit involves stakeholders with different roles, incentives, and conflicts of interest:

Stakeholder	Role in the system	Incentive for Audit	Potential conflict of interest
Developers/Data Scientists	Build, train, and deploy the model	Demonstrate technical competence, deploy working systems	May rationalize disparities to defend their own design choices
External Auditors	Independent technical review	Their reputation depends on rigor and independence of audit	May lack full access to data, model internals, technical expertise or business context
Affected Individuals/Communities	Vulnerable to unfair model decisions	Direct stake in fair treatment	Often lack technical expertise or institutional access
Regulators/legislators	Enforce standards and regulation	Public accountability	Slow to act compared to how quickly models change
