Findings from MAP:

-As shown by the bar graphs, the dataset is heavily imbalanced. It contains 67% male and 33% female participants.

-The base right of income >50k is about 3x higher for men than for women, which already reflects historical wage inequalities.

-So, any classifier that is trained on this imbalanced data without any intervention will probably reproduce or amplify these disparities.

The fairness question is not whether disparities exist (clearly, they do), but how the model should be evaluated and whose judgment determines what counts as acceptable.

This is the moment in the audit where the choice of auditor really matters. An internal team focused on accuracy may treat the base-rate disparity as "ground truth" since they care about accuracy. An external auditor that is more focused on stakeholder engagement may treat these results as evidence that fairness cannot be reduced to predictive accuracy alone.

3. MEASURE: Baseline Classifier and Fairness Metrics
The MEASURE function evaluates the trained model along multiple dimensions: overall performance, disaggregated performance across protected groups, and fairness-specific metrics. We use Fairlearn's MetricFrame for disaggregated views and AIF360's ClassificationMetric for disparate impact and statistical parity difference.

3.1 Train/Test Split and Baseline Model
Predict whether a person (split by sex) makes more than 50k a year (high earner) using a simple logistic regression model on the UCI data, and compute performance metrics (accuracy and Area under ROC Curve, which measures false positive vs. true positive rate).

