3.5 Internal vs. External Interpretation of the Same Metrics
The numbers above are mathematically unambiguous. Their interpretation, however, depends on the auditor.

Metric	What an internal team might say	What an external auditor might say
Overall accuracy ~0.85	"The model is accurate! Deploy it."	"Overall accuracy does not show which subgroup absorbs the errors."
Selection rate disparity (Male ~26%, Female ~10%)	"This reflects real base-rate differences in the training data."	"The model is offering fewer positive predictions to women regardless of merit, which amplifies the disparity."
Disparate impact ~0.35	"Although it is below the 0.8 four-fifths threshold, the underlying base rates differ, which we can't fix."	"Disparate impact this severe would not survive an EEOC employment-discrimination challenge."
Equal opportunity difference	"The TPR gap is small, so qualified women are still being identified."	"Even a small TPR gap, applied at scale, denies opportunity to thousands of qualified individuals."
4. MANAGE: Mitigation Strategies and Re-Measurement
The MANAGE function applies risk-treatment strategies from both repositories and re-evaluates the system. We apply 2 mitigations of different types:

Reweighing (AIF360, preprocessing) adjusts training-instance weights so that the protected attribute and outcome become statistically independent in the training distribution. The model itself is unchanged; only the data weights are.
Threshold Optimization (Fairlearn, postprocessing) keeps the model fixed but learns separate decision thresholds per group to satisfy a specified fairness constraint. Here we use demographic parity as the constraint.
